clinical_study.brief_title: Comparing The Performance Of Two Different Daily Disposable Lenses (MIKI)
clinical_study.official_title: Comparing The Performance Of Two Different Daily Disposable Lenses (MIKI)

brief_summary.textblock: The objective of the study is to evaluate and compare the performance of study test lens to study control lens, when worn on a daily disposable modality over a period of approximately one week each

detailed_description.textblock: The study is a prospective, double masked (investigator and participant), bilateral, randomized,one week cross-over dispensing study, which evaluates the study test lens and control lens.

primary_outcome.description: Overall fit acceptance (0-4, 0.50 steps) (0 - lens should not be worn at all,1 - Borderline but unacceptable, 2 - Minimally acceptable, 3 - Not perfect but OK to dispense, 4 - Perfect)

secondary_outcome.description: Lens Centration was measured on a scale (0-3) (0 = "Optimally centered", 1 = "Slightly decentered", 2 = Moderate decentration but not encroaching limbus, 3 = "Excessive & occasionally encroaching limbus")

Lens Centration was measured on a scale (0-3) (0 = "Optimally centered", 1 = "Slightly decentered", 2 = Moderate decentration but not encroaching limbus, 3 = "Excessive & occasionally encroaching limbus")
Post-blink lens movement was measured using an eyepiece reticule while viewing the contact lens in-vivo at 8x magnification in primary gaze, in 0.1mm steps
Post-blink lens movement was measured using an eyepiece reticule while viewing the contact lens in-vivo at 8x magnification in primary gaze, in 0.1mm steps
Push-up tightness in primary gaze measured on a scale (0-100, 5% steps) (0% = falls from cornea without lid support, 50% = optimum, 100% = no movement)
Push-up tightness in primary gaze measured on a scale (0-100, 5% steps) (0% = falls from cornea without lid support, 50% = optimum and 100% = no movement)
